Mexican presidential frontrunner Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador extended his lead to nearly 17 points over his nearest rival ahead of the July 1 vote, according to a poll published on Sunday. https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mexico-election-poll/mexican-leftist-frontrunner-widens-lead-for-presidency-poll-idUSKBN1J700K?il=0
No Mexican presidential election candidate has won more than 50% of the vote since 1988. Current polling shows Obrador with twice the support of his closest rival.

I used to hear about Obrado on international channels. I think he was Mayor of Mexico City. He has been around for a long time. Although he favors socialism and so on, he is a good guy, a stabilizing influence. US policy or rather domination and influence in their governments and elections in Latin America has been waning a little for years. His ability to challenge for the election is a reflection of this. But it's easy for me to have opinions because I don't have property or financial interests in Mexico. I have faith he would treat everyone fairly.
I think he will receive a boost due to anti-Trump sentiment in Mexico over and above his current popularity

Obrador ran twice before and lost. Last time won just under 32%. He is clearly the front runner at this stage but there has to some chance he de-rails for some reason or other, or as another forecaster reminds, simply has ill health or some other such reason why he cannot win. So a small probability of ‘no’ is warranted. To win more than 50% of the vote would seem to require a really substantial shift in voters’ views on Obrador and I don’t know enough to make that claim.
Let’s cover the 4%. Random things can happen from death to opponent boosting events. The time is running down for this to have a high probability.
